
				<exercises>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.3) </p></aside>
							Let
							<m> A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix},
								B = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \amp 2\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix},
								C = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
								D = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \\ -1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix},</m> and
							<m>
								E = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
							</m> Compute the following (where possible).
							 <ol cols="3">
								<li>
									<m> 3A - 2B </m>
								</li>
								<li> 
									<m> 5C </m>
								</li>
								<li> 
									<m> 3E^T </m>
								</li>
								<li> 
							-		<m> B+D </m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m> 4A^T - 3C </m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m> (A+C)^T </m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m> 2B - 3E </m>
								</li>
								<li> 
									<m> A - D </m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m>(B- 2E)^T </m>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
						<hint><aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Definition 2.1) </p></aside>
							Recall: If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are matrices of the same size, their <em>sum</em> <m>A+B</m> is the matrix formed by adding corresponding entries.
						</hint>
						<hint><aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Definition 2.2) </p></aside>
							Recall: If <m>A</m> is any matrix and <m>k</m> is any number, the <em>scalar multiple</em> <m>kA</m> is the matrix obtained from <m>A</m> by multiplying each entry of <m>A</m> by <m>k</m> .
						</hint>
						<hint xml:id="hint-matrix-transpose"><aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Definition 2.3) </p></aside>
							Recall: If <m>A</m> is a <m>m\times n</m> matrix, the <em>transpose</em> of <m>A</m>, written <m>A^T</m>, is the <m>n\times m</m> matrix whose rows are just the columns of  <m>A</m> in the same order.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							<ol>
								<li><solution>
									We cannot add these matrices as they are not of the same size (<m>3A</m> is a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix, while <m>2B</m> is a <m>2\times 3</m> matrix).
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution> 
									<me> 5C = 5\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 15 \amp -5 \\ 10 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									<me> 3E^T = 3 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}^{T}
									=3 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0  \\  0  \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0  \\  0  \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
									 </me>
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution> 
									We cannot add these matrices as they are not of the same size (<m>-B</m> is a <m>2\times 3</m> matrix, while <m>D</m> is a <m>3\times 2</m> matrix).
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									<md>
										<mrow>4A^T - 3C \amp = 4 \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}^T - 3\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
										<mrow>\amp = 4 \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 9 \amp -3 \\ 6 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
										<mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 8 - 9 \amp 0 - (-3) \\ 4 - 6 \amp -4 - 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>										
										<mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 3 \\ -2 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									<md>
										<mrow>(A+C)^T \amp = \left( \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \\ 2 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\right)^T </mrow>
										<mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}^T </mrow>
										<mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									<md>
										<mrow> 2B - 3E \amp = 2 \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \amp 2\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} - 3 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
										<mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \amp -2 \amp 4\\ 0 \amp 2 \amp 8 \end{bmatrix}
											- \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
										<mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -2 \amp 1\\ 0 \amp -1 \amp 8 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution> 
									We cannot add these matrices as they are not of the same size (<m>A</m> is a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix, while <m>-D</m> is a is a <m>3\times 2</m> matrix).
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									<md>
										<mrow> (B- 2E)^T \amp = \left( \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \amp 2\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix} - 2 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\right)^{T}</mrow>
										<mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 - 2 \amp -1 - 0 \amp 2 - 2\\ 0 - 0 \amp 1 - 2 \amp 4 - 0 \end{bmatrix}^{T}</mrow>
										<mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \amp 0\\ 0 \amp -1 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}^{T}</mrow>
										<mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0 \\ -1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</solution></li>
							</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
								<li><answer>
									Does not exist.
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer> 
									<me> 5C = \begin{bmatrix} 15 \amp -5 \\ 10 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									<me> 3E^T =
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0  \\  0  \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
									 </me>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer> 
									Does not exist.
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									<md>
										<mrow>4A^T - 3C \amp = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 3 \\ -2 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									<md>
										<mrow>(A+C)^T \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									<md>
										<mrow> 2B - 3E \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -2 \amp 1\\ 0 \amp -1 \amp 8 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer> 
									Does not exist.
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									<md>
										<mrow> (B- 2E)^T \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1\amp 0 \\ -1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</answer></li>
							</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p>(Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 4, Exercise 4.4.6) </p></aside>

							Consider the matrices:
							<m> A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix},
								B = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\ -3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},
								C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},
								D = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp -3 \end{bmatrix}, </m>
							and <m>
								E = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}.</m>  Find the following if possible. If it is not possible, explain why.
							<ol cols="3">
								<li>
									<m> -3A </m>
								</li>
								<li> 
									<m> 3B - A </m>
								</li>
								<li> 
									<m> AC </m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m> CB </m>
								</li>
								<li> 
									<m> AE </m>
								</li>
								<li>
									<m> EA </m>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
						<hint xml:id="hint-matrix-product">
							<aside><p>(Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 4, Definition 4.21) </p></aside>
							Recall: Let <m>A=[a_{i j}]</m> be an <m>m\times n</m>-matrix, and let <m>B=[b_{j k}]</m> be an <m>n\times p</m>-matrix. Then their <em>product</em> is the <m>m\times p</m>-matrix
							<m>AB= [c_{ik}]</m> whose <m>(i,k)</m>-entry is defined by
							<me>
								c_{ik} = a_{i1}b_{1k}+a_{i2}b_{2k}+...+a_{in}b_{nk}.
							</me>
						</hint>
						<solution>
							<ol>
								<li><solution>
									<md><mrow> -3A \amp= -3\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}
										=\begin{bmatrix} -3 \amp -6 \amp -9\\ -6 \amp -3 \amp -21 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow></md>
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution> 
									<md><mrow> 3B - A \amp =3\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\ -3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} - \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
									<mrow> \amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} 3\cdot 3 -1 \amp 3\cdot (-1) - 2 \amp 3\cdot 2 - 3 \\ 3\cdot (-3) -2 \amp 3\cdot 2 -1 \amp 3\cdot 1 -7 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
									<mrow> \amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp -5 \amp 3 \\ -11 \amp 5 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution> 
									We cannot multiply these matrices as their sizes do not match up: the number of columns in <m>A</m> does not coincide with the number of rows in <m>C</m>.
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									<md><mrow> CB \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -1 \amp 2 \\ -3 \amp 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
									<mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \cdot 3 + 2\cdot (-3) \amp 1\cdot (-1) + 2\cdot 2 \amp 1\cdot 2 + 2\cdot 1 \\ 3 \cdot 3 + 1\cdot (-3) \amp 3\cdot (-1) + 1\cdot 2 \amp 3\cdot 2 + 1\cdot 1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
									<mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} -3 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 6 \amp -1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow></md>
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution> 
									We cannot multiply these matrices as their sizes do not match up: the number of columns in <m>A</m> does not coincide with the number of rows in <m>E</m>.
								</solution></li>
								<li><solution>
									We cannot multiply these matrices as their sizes do not match up: the number of columns in <m>E</m> does not coincide with the number of rows in <m>A</m>.
								</solution></li>
							</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
								<li><answer>
									<md><mrow> -3A \amp=\begin{bmatrix} -3 \amp -6 \amp -9\\ -6 \amp -3 \amp -21 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow></md>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer> 
									<md><mrow> 3B - A \amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} 8 \amp -5 \amp 3 \\ -11 \amp 5 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow>
									</md>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer> 
									Does not exist.
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									<md><mrow> CB = \begin{bmatrix} -3 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 6 \amp -1 \amp 7 \end{bmatrix}.</mrow></md>
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer> 
									Does not exist.
								</answer></li>
								<li><answer>
									Does not exist.
								</answer></li>
							</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 1, Exercise 1.3.6) </p></aside>
							Write the following system of linear equations as an augmented matrix (of the form <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}</m>).
							<md>
								<mrow>
									x - 3z - 2y \amp =  5
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									6 -x \amp =  4+y - z
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									2x + 3 \amp =  x+3y
								</mrow>
							</md>
						</statement>
						 <hint>
						 	First simplify and rearrange the equations so that ''like'' variables are lined up in columns.  Write the variables in the order <m>x,y,z</m>.
						</hint> 
						<solution>
							We sort by ''like'' variables:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									x - 2y  - 3z \amp =  5
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									-x - y + z \amp =  -2
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									x -3y  \amp = -3
								</mrow>
							</md>
							Now we can easily write it as augmented matrix:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{ccc|c}{
										1 \amp  -2  \amp - 3 \amp   5\\
										-1 \amp -1	\amp 1 \amp   -2\\
										1 \amp -3  \amp 0 \amp  -3
									}.
								</mrow>
							</md>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\matr{ccc|c}{
										1 \amp  -2  \amp - 3 \amp   5\\
										-1 \amp -1	\amp 1 \amp   -2\\
										1 \amp -3  \amp 0 \amp  -3
									}
								</mrow>
							</md>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.3.29) </p></aside>
							Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be <m>n \times n</m> matrices for which the system  of equations  <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m> and <m>B\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m> each only have the trivial solution <m>\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m>.  Show that the system <m>AB \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m> has only the trivial solution.
						</statement>
						<hint>
							Assume that <m>\mathbf{y}</m> is a solution to the system <m>AB \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m>. Use the assumptions to conclude that we must have <m>\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{0}</m>.
						</hint>
						<hint>
							Remember that <m>AB \mathbf{x} = A(B \mathbf{x}) =(AB) \mathbf{x}</m>.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							Take any vector <m>\mathbf{y}</m> with <m>n</m> components such that <m>AB \mathbf{y} = \mathbf{0}</m>. This means that <m>B \mathbf{y}</m> is a solution to the system of equations  <m>A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m> which, by assumption, only has the trivial solution. In other words, <m>B \mathbf{y} = \mathbf{0}</m>. This similarly means that <m>\mathbf{y}</m> is a solution to the system of equations  <m>B\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m> which, again by assumption, only has the trivial solution. Thus, <m>\mathbf{y}=\mathbf{0}</m>. We have seen that the system <m>AB \mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}</m> only has the trivial solution.
						</solution>
						<!--answer makes no sense here.-->
					</exercise></p>
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.3.27) </p></aside>
							 In each case either show the statement is true or give an example showing that it is false. (We assume that the matrices are of the correct size so that all matrix products which we consider make sense.)
	<ol>
		<li> 
			If <m> A^2 = I</m>, then <m> A = I</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			If <m> AB = A</m>, then <m> B = I</m>. 
		</li>
		<li> 
		 	If <m> A </m> is square, then <m> (A^T)^3 = (A^3)^T</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			If <m>A</m> is symmetric, then <m> I + A</m> is symmetric.
		</li>
		<li>
			If <m> AB = AC </m> and <m> A \ne 0</m>, then <m> B = C </m>. 
		</li>
		<li> 
		  	If <m> A \ne 0</m>, then <m> A^2 \ne 0</m>.
		 </li>		 
		<li>
			If <m> A </m> commutes with <m> A+B </m> then <m> A </m> commutes with <m> B </m>.
		</li>
	</ol>

			</statement>
				<hint xml:id="hint-def-symmetric">
					<p>See <xref ref="hint-matrix-transpose"/> for the definition of the transpose and <xref ref="hint-matrix-product"/> for the definition of matrix multiplication.</p>

					<p>Look back into <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Theorem 2.1.1, for some properties of matrix operation.</p>
					
					<p>A square matrix <m>A</m> is called <em>symmetric</em> if <m>A=A^T</m>.</p>

					<p>Two square matrices <m>A,B</m> of the same size are said to <em>commute</em> if <m>AB=BA</m>.</p>
				</hint>
				<hint>
					All counterexamples can be chosen to be of size <m>2\times 2</m>.
				</hint>
				<solution>
					<ol>
					<li><solution> 
						<em>False:</em> Take <m> A =\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}\neq I</m>, which satisfies <m> A^2 = I</m>.
					</solution></li>
					<li><solution>
						<em>False:</em> Take <m>A=B=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0\end{bmatrix}\neq I</m>, which satisfy <m> AB = A</m>.
					</solution></li>
					<li><solution> 
						<!--If <m> A </m> is square, then <m> (A^T)^3 = (A^3)^T</m>.-->
						<em>True:</em> We will prove that <m>B^T A^T=(AB)^T</m>, which will imply our claim because
						<me>
							(A^T)^3 = (A^T)(A^T)(A^T) = A^T(AA)^T = ((AA)A)^T = (A^3)^T.
						</me>
						For this proof, let us write <m>A_{i,j}</m> for the <m>(i,j)</m>-entry of <m>A</m>. Thus, we know from <xref ref="hint-matrix-product"/> that the <m>(i,k)</m>-entry of <m>AB</m> is given by:
						<me>
							(AB)_{i,k} = A_{i,1}B_{1,k}+A_{i,2}B_{2,k}+...+A_{i,n}B_{n,k}.
						</me>
						Recall further from <xref ref="hint-matrix-transpose"/> that <m>(B^T)_{k,j}=B_{j k}</m> and <m>(A^{T})_{j,i}=A_{i j}</m>, so that <m>B^T A^T</m> has <m>(k,i)</m>-entry 
						<md>
							<mrow>(B^T A^T)_{k,i} \amp= (B^T)_{k,1}(A^T)_{1,i}+(B^T)_{k,2}(A^T)_{2,i}+...+(B^T)_{k,n}(A^T)_{n,i}</mrow>
							<mrow>\amp = B{1,k}A_{i,1}+B_{2,k}A_{i,2}+...+B_{n,k}A_{i,n}</mrow>					
							<mrow>\amp = (AB)_{i,k}.</mrow>
						</md> 
						Again by <xref ref="hint-matrix-transpose"/>, <m>(i,k)</m>-entry of <m>AB</m> is the same as the <m>(k,i)</m>-entry of <m>(AB)^T</m>, so that 
						<me>
							(B^T A^T)_{k,i}= (AB)_{i,k} = ((AB)^T)_{k,i} .
						</me>
					 	We have shown that the <m>(k,i)</m>-entry of <m>B^T A^T</m> and of <m>(AB)^T</m> are identical. This means that <m>B^T A^T=(AB)^T</m>.
					</solution></li>
					<li><solution>
						<em>True:</em> <m>A</m> is symmetric means <m>A=A^T</m>. Thus, <m> (I + A)^{T} = I^{T}+A^{T} = I+A</m>,  where the first equality follows from Theorem 2.1.2(4) in <xref ref="ref-KN"/>. Thus, <m> I + A</m> is symmetric as well.
					</solution></li>
					<li><solution>
						<em>False:</em> Let
							<me>
								A=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
								B=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},
								C=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}.
							</me>
						Then <m> A \ne 0</m> and 
						<me> AB = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} = A = AC, </me>
						but <m> B \neq C </m>. 
					</solution></li>
					<li><solution> 
					  	<em>False:</em> Let <m>A=\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>. Then <m> A^2 = 0</m>, even though <m>A\neq 0</m>.
					 </solution></li>							 
					<li><solution>
						<em>True:</em> We compute
						<me> A^2 + AB = A(A+B) \overset{(*)}{=} (A+B)A = A^2 + BA,</me>
						where <m>(*)</m> is by assumption that <m>A</m> commutes with <m>A+B</m>. If we substract <m>A^{2}</m> from both the left- and right-most side of the equation, we see that <m>AB=BA</m>, i.e. <m>A</m> commutes with <m> B </m>.
					</solution></li>
				</ol>
				</solution>
				<answer>
					<ol>
					<li>False.</li>
					<li>False.</li>
					<li>True.</li>
					<li>True.</li>
					<li>False.</li>
					<li>False.</li>							 
					<li>True.</li>
				</ol>
				</answer>

			</exercise></p>
			<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
				<statement>
					<aside><p> (Adapted from: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.3.27) </p></aside>
					 In each case either show the statement is true or give an example showing that it is false. (We assume that the matrices are of the correct size so that all matrix products which we consider make sense.)
	<ol>
		<li>
			If <m> B</m>  has a row of zeros, so also does <m> AB</m> for all <m> A</m>.
		</li>y		
		<li>  
			If <m> A </m> has a row of zeros, so also does <m> AB </m> for all <m> B</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			If <m> B</m> has a column of zeros, so also does <m> AB </m>  for all <m>A</m>.
		</li>
		<li> 
			If <m> AB </m> has a column of zeros for some <m>A\neq 0</m>, then so also does <m> B</m>.
		</li>
		<li>
			If <m> AB </m> has a row of zeros for some <m>A\neq 0</m>, so also does <m> B </m>.			
		</li>
	</ol>

			</statement>
						<solution>
							<ol>
							 <li><solution>
							 	<!--If <m> B</m>  has a row of zeros, so also does <m> AB</m> for all <m> A</m>. -->
							 	<em>False:</em> Let
							 	<me>
							 		A=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} 
									\text{ and }									
									B=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
								</me>
								Then <m>AB = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> does not have a zero row.
							</solution></li>							
							<li><solution>  
								<!-- If <m> A </m> has a row of zeros, so also does <m> AB </m> for all <m> B</m>. -->
								<em>True:</em> Let us write <m>A= [ a_{ij}]</m> and <m>B= [ b_{jk}]</m>. By assumption, there exists a zero row in <m>A</m>, say row <m>i_{0}</m>. In other words, <m>a_{i_{0}j}=0</m> for all <m>j</m>. By definition of <m>AB= [c_{ik}]</m> (see <xref ref="hint-matrix-product"/>), its <m>(i,k)</m>-entry is defined by
								<me>
									c_{ik} = a_{i1}b_{1k}+a_{i2}b_{2k}+...+a_{in}b_{nk}.
								</me>
								Since <m>a_{i_{0}j}=0</m> for all <m>j</m>, we see that <m>c_{i_{0}k}=0</m> for all <m>k</m>. In other words, row <m>i_{0}</m> in <m>AB</m> is zero.
							</solution></li>
							<li><solution>
								<!-- If <m> B</m> has a column of zeros, so also does <m> AB </m>  for all <m>A</m>. -->
								<em>True:</em> Let us write <m>A= [ a_{ij}]</m> and <m>B= [ b_{jk}]</m>. By assumption, there exists a zero column in <m>B</m>, say column <m>k_{0}</m>. In other words, <m>b_{jk_{0}}=0</m> for all <m>j</m>. By definition of <m>AB= [c_{ik}]</m> (see <xref ref="hint-matrix-product"/>), its <m>(i,k)</m>-entry is defined by
								<me>
									c_{ik} = a_{i1}b_{1k}+a_{i2}b_{2k}+...+a_{in}b_{nk}.
								</me>
								Since <m>b_{jk_{0}}=0</m> for all <m>j</m>, we see that <m>c_{ik_{0}}=0</m> for all <m>i</m>. In other words, column <m>k_{0}</m> in <m>AB</m> is zero.
							</solution></li>
							<li><solution> 
								<!-- If <m> AB </m> has a column of zeros for some <m>A\neq 0</m>, then so also does <m> B</m>. -->
								<em>False:</em> Take 
								<me>
									A=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \\ 2 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix} 
									\text{ and }
									B=\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix},
								</me>
								so that
								<me>
									AB 
									=\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} .
								</me>
							</solution></li>
							<li><solution> 
								<!-- If <m> AB </m> has a row of zeros for some <m>A\neq 0</m>, so also does <m> B </m>.	 -->
								<em>False:</em> Take
								<me>
									A=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp -2 \\ 2 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix} 
									\text{ and }
									B=\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix},
								</me>
								so that
								<me>
									AB 
									=\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix} .
								</me>
							</solution></li>
						</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
							 <li>
							 	<!--If <m> B</m>  has a row of zeros, so also does <m> AB</m> for all <m> A</m>. -->
							 	False.
							</li>							
							<li><!-- If <m> A </m> has a row of zeros, so also does <m> AB </m> for all <m> B</m>. -->
								True.</li>
							<li><!-- If <m> B</m> has a column of zeros, so also does <m> AB </m>  for all <m>A</m>. -->
								True.</li>
							<li><!-- If <m> AB </m> has a column of zeros for some <m>A\neq 0</m>, then so also does <m> B</m>. -->
								False. 
							</li>
							<li><!-- If <m> AB </m> has a row of zeros for some <m>A\neq 0</m>, so also does <m> B </m>.	 -->
								False.</li>
						</ol>
						</answer>

					</exercise></p>

					
					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
						<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.5) </p></aside>
						Find <m> A </m> in terms of <m> B </m> if: 
						<ol cols="2">
							<li> 
								<me> A + B = 3A + 2B </me>
							</li>
							<li>
								<me>
									2A - B = 5(A + 2B) </me>
							</li>
						</ol>
					</statement>
						<hint>
							Theorem 2.1.1 in Section 2.1 of <xref ref="ref-KN" /> might help.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							Because of the properties listed in Theorem 2.1.1 of <xref ref="ref-KN" />, we can manipulate both sides of the equations just like we would if <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> were numbers:
							<ol>
							<li> 
								<md>
									<mrow> A + B = 3A + 2B \iff \amp (1-3)A = (2-1)B </mrow>									
									<mrow>\iff \amp -2A = B </mrow>																
									<mrow>\iff \amp A= -\frac{1}{2} B. </mrow>
								</md>
							</li>
							<li>
								<md>
									<mrow>2A - B = 5(A + 2B)  \iff \amp 2A - B = 5A + 10B</mrow>
									<mrow>\iff \amp -3A = 11B</mrow>
									<mrow>\iff \amp A = -\frac{11}{3}B. </mrow>
								</md>
							</li>
						</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol cols="2">
							<li> 
								<me> A= -\frac{1}{2} B  </me>
							</li>
							<li>
								<me>
									A = -\frac{11}{3}B 
								</me>
							</li>
						</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
 					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.6) </p></aside>
							If <m> X, Y, A, </m> and <m> B </m> are matrices of the same size, solve the following systems of equations to obtain <m> X </m> and <m> Y </m> in terms of <m> A </m> and <m> B </m>.
							<ol cols="2">
								<li>
									<md>
										<mrow>
											5X + 3Y  \amp =  A
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											2X + Y  \amp =  B
										</mrow>
									</md>
								</li>
								<li>
									<md>
										<mrow>
											4X + 3Y  \amp =  A
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											5X + 4Y  \amp =  B
										</mrow>
									</md>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
						<hint>
							It might help to look back into Theorem 2.1.1 of <xref ref="ref-KN" />.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							Because of the properties listed in Theorem 2.1.1 of <xref ref="ref-KN" />, we can manipulate both sides of the equations just like we would if <m>A, B</m> were numbers and <m>X, Y</m> were variables (however, we cannot simply divide by a matrix!).
							<ol>
								<li> <solution>The system can also be written as
									<me>
										\matr{cc|c}{ 5 \amp 3 \amp A \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp B},
									</me>
									where it is important that we remember that <m>A,B</m> are not numbers, so we cannot divide by them. We row-reduce:
									<md>
										<mrow>\matr{cc|c}{5 \amp 3 \amp A
												\\ 	2 \amp 1 \amp B}
										\underset{5R_{2}}{\overset{2R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}}
										\amp
										\matr{cc|c}{10 \amp 6 \amp 2A
												\\ 	10 \amp 5 \amp 5B}
										\overset{-R_{1}+R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}
										\matr{cc|c}{10 \amp 6 \amp 2A
												\\ 	0 \amp -1 \amp 5B-2A}
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
										\overset{6R_{2}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
										\amp
										\matr{cc|c}{10 \amp 0 \amp 2A + 6 (5B-2A)
												\\ 	0 \amp -1 \amp 5B-2A}
											</mrow><mrow>
										\amp=
										\matr{cc|c}{10 \amp 0 \amp -10A + 30 B
										\\ 	0 \amp -1 \amp 5B-2A}.
										</mrow>
									</md>
									We conclude that <m> X= \frac{1}{10} (-10A + 30 B) = -A + 3 B</m> and <m>Y=-5B+2A</m>.</solution>
								</li>
								<li><solution>The system can also be written as
									<me>
										\matr{cc|c}{ 4 \amp 3 \amp A \\ 5 \amp 4 \amp B},
									</me>
									where it is important that we remember that <m>A,B</m> are not numbers, so we cannot divide by them. We row-reduce:
									<md>
										<mrow>
											\matr{cc|c}{ 4 \amp 3 \amp A
														\\ 5 \amp 4 \amp B}
											\overset{5R_{1}}{\underset{4R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}}
											\amp\matr{cc|c}{ 20 \amp 15 \amp 5A
														\\ 20 \amp 16 \amp 4B}
											\overset{-R_{1}+R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}										
											\matr{cc|c}{ 20 \amp 15 \amp 5A
														\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4B-5A}
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											\overset{-15R_{2}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
											\amp\matr{cc|c}{ 20 \amp 0 \amp 5A-15(4B-5A)
														\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4B-5A}
										</mrow>
										<mrow>
											\amp=\matr{cc|c}{ 20 \amp 0 \amp 80A-60B
														\\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 4B-5A}
										</mrow>
									</md>
									We conclude that <m> X= \frac{1}{20} (80A-60B) = 4A - 3 B</m> and <m>Y=4B-5A</m>.</solution>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
								<li> <answer><m> X= -A + 3 B</m>, <m>Y=-5B+2A</m>.</answer>
								</li>
								<li><answer>
									<m> X= 4A - 3 B</m>, <m>Y=4B-5A</m>
								</answer>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
						<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
						<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-PS" />, Chapter 9, Exercise 9.2.7) </p></aside>
						Determine whether  each of the following sets of matrices is linearly indpendent.  If it is linearly independent, write one matrix as a linear combination of the other matrices in the set. 
						<ol>
							<li> 
								<me> \left\{ \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix} -7 \amp 2 \\ -2\amp -3 \end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}\right\}  </me>
							</li>
							<li>
								<me>
									\left\{ \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0\amp 1 \end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}\right\} </me>
							</li>
						</ol>
					</statement>
						<hint xml:id="hint-matrix-linear-dependence">
							Matrices <m>A_{1}, \ldots, A_{m}</m> of the same size are called <em>linearly dependent</em> if there exist numbers <m>c_{1},\ldots, c_{m}</m>, not all of which are zero, so that 
							<me>
								c_{1}A_{1}+c_{2}A_{2}+\ldots + c_{m}A_{m} = 0.
							</me>
							Otherwise, they are called <em>linearly independent</em>. 
						</hint>
						<hint xml:id="hint-matrix-linear-independence">
							Another way of phrasing linear independence is: Matrices <m>A_{1}, \ldots, A_{m}</m> of the same size are linearly independent if the only solution <m>(c_{1}, \ldots, c_{m})</m> to the system of linear equations
							<me>
								x_{1}A_{1}+x_{2}A_{2}+\ldots + x_{m}A_{m} = 0
							</me>
							is the trivial solution, <m>(0,\ldots, 0).</m>
						</hint>
						<solution>							
							<ol>
							<li> <solution>We are wondering whether there exist numbers <m>x,y,z</m>, not all zero, such that
								<me>
									x \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
									+ y\begin{bmatrix} -7 \amp 2 \\ -2\amp -3 \end{bmatrix}
									+ z\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}\right\} 
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}.
								</me>
								Note that an equality of matrices means componentwise equality, so for example, the equality of the <m>(1,1)</m>-entry says:
								<me> x - 7 y + 4 z = 0.</me>
								Proceeding in this way, we arrive at a system of 4 linear equations with augmented matrix that we can row-reduce:
								<md><mrow>
									\matr{ccc|c}
									{
										1 \amp -7 \amp 4 \amp 0
										\\
										2 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp 0
									}
									\overset{-2R_{1}+R_{2}}{\underset{-R_{1}+R_{4}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp\matr{ccc|c}
									{
										1 \amp -7 \amp 4 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 16 \amp -8 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 5 \amp -2 \amp 0
									}
									\overset{8R_{3}+R_{2}}{\underset{2R_{4}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\matr{ccc|c}
									{
										1 \amp -7 \amp 4 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 10 \amp -4 \amp 0
									}</mrow>
									<mrow>
									\overset{5R_{3}+R_{4}}{\longrightarrow}
									\amp \matr{ccc|c}
									{
										1 \amp -7 \amp 4 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0
									}</mrow>
									<!-- <mrow>
									\overset{-R_{4}+R_{3}}{\underset{-4R_{4}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp \matr{ccc|c}
									{
										1 \amp -7 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0
									}</mrow>
									<mrow>
									\overset{-R_{4}+R_{3}}{\underset{-4R_{4}+R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}}
									\amp \matr{ccc|c}
									{
										1 \amp -7 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 0
										\\
										0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0
									}</mrow> -->
									.
								</md>
								At this point, we can already see that further row reduction will yield that the only solution is <m>(x,y,z)=(0,0,0)</m>. Therefore, the matrices are linearly independent.
							</solution>
							</li>
							<li><solution>We are wondering whether there exist numbers <m>w,x,y,z</m>, not all zero, such that
								<me>
									w\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
									+x\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0\amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
									+y\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
									+z\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								</me>
								Just as in the last part, we could turn this into an augmented matrix of size <m>4\times 5</m> and row-reduce, but since the entries of these matrices are easier, we will do it by hand: <p>Equality of the <m>(1,2)</m>-entries says that <m>x=0</m>.</p> <p>Equality of the <m>(1,1)</m>-entries says that <m>w+y=0</m>, i.e. <m>w=-y</m>.</p> <p>Equality of the <m>(2,1)</m>-entries says that <m>y+z=0</m>, i.e. <m>z=-y=w</m>.</p><p> Lastly, equality of the <m>(2,2)</m>-entries says that <m>w+x+z=0</m>, which means that <m>w=-z</m> since <m>x=0</m>.</p> <p>Since <m>-z=w=z</m> also, we conclude that <m>z=0</m> and so also <m>0=z=-y=w</m>. All in all, the only solution is <m>(w,x,y,z)=(0,0,0,0)</m>, so the matrices are linearly independent.</p></solution>
							</li>
						</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
							<li> <answer>The matrices are linearly independent.
							</answer>
							</li>
							<li><answer>The matrices are linearly independent.</answer>
							</li>
						</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

						<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
						<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-RB" />, LISS.C20 </p></aside> <!-- Anna Thinks that ref-RB has other numbers in the matrices, but whatever.-->
						Let 
						<me>  S = \left\{ \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix} \right\}</me>
						<ol>
							<li> 
								Determine if <m> S </m> spans the set of all <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrices.
							</li>
							<li>
								Determine if <m> S </m> is linearly independent.
							</li>
						</ol>


						</statement>
						<!-- <hint>
							span
						</hint> -->						
						<hint>
							See <xml ref="hint-matrix-linear-dependence"/> and <xml ref="hint-matrix-linear-independence"/> for the definition of linear independence.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							<ol>
							<li><solution xml:id="soln-3-2-4a">
								The set <m> S </m> spans the set of all <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrices if and only if, for any <m> 2 \times 2 </m> matrix <m>A</m>, there exist numbers <m>x_{1}, x_{2}, x_{3}</m> so that
								<me>
									x_{1} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
									+ x_{2}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
									+ x_{3} \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									A
									.
								</me>
								If we write <m> A = \begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>, then this is equivalent to saying that there exists a solution to the following system of linear equations:
								<md>
									<mrow>
										x_{1} + 2x_{2}  \amp = a
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										2 x_{1} + x_{2} + x_{3} \amp= b
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										2x_{1} - x_{2} + x_{3} \amp = c
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										x_{1} + 2x_{2} + 2x_{3} \amp = d
									</mrow>
								</md>
								Let us transfer this into an augmented matrix and then row-reduce:
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\amp\matr{ccc|c}
										{
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp a
										 \\
										 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp b
										 \\
										 2 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp c
										 \\
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp d
										}
										\overset{-R_{1}+R_{4}}{\underset{-2R_{1}+R_{3}, -2R_{1}+R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}}					
										\matr{ccc|c}
										{
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp a
										 \\
										 0 \amp -3 \amp 1 \amp b-2a
										 \\
										 0 \amp -5 \amp 1 \amp c-2a
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp d - a
										}
									</mrow>									
									<mrow>
										\amp\overset{\frac{1}{2}R_{4}}{\underset{-R_{4}'+R_{3}, -R_{4}'+R_{2}}{\longrightarrow}}					
										\matr{ccc|c}
										{
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp a
										 \\
										 0 \amp -3 \amp 0 \amp b-2a -\frac{1}{2}(d - a)
										 \\
										 0 \amp -5 \amp 0 \amp c-2a - \frac{1}{2}(d - a)
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{2}(d - a)
										}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp\overset{5R_{2}}{\underset{-3R_{3}}{\longrightarrow}}					
										\matr{ccc|c}
										{
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp a
										 \\
										 0 \amp -15 \amp 0 \amp 5b-\frac{15}{2}a  -\frac{5}{2}d
										 \\
										 0 \amp 15 \amp 0 \amp -3c+ \frac{9}{2}a + \frac{3}{2}d 
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{2}(d - a)
										}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp\overset{R_{2}+R_{3}}{\longrightarrow}
										\matr{ccc|c}
										{
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp a
										 \\
										 0 \amp -15 \amp 0 \amp 5b-\frac{15}{2}a  -\frac{5}{2}d
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp (-3c+ \frac{9}{2}a + \frac{3}{2}d)  + (5b-\frac{15}{2}a  -\frac{5}{2}d)
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp \frac{1}{2}(d - a)
										}.
									</mrow>
								</md>
								We see from the third row that the system is inconsistent if 
								<me>
									-3c -3 a - d  + 5b   
									=
									\left(-3c+ \frac{9}{2}a + \frac{3}{2}d)  + (5b-\frac{15}{2}a  -\frac{5}{2}d\right)
									\neq 0.
								</me>
								Since <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> is an example of a choice of numbers which makes the system inconsistent, we conclude that, no, <m>S</m> does not span the set of all <m>2\times 2</m> matrices.
							</solution></li>
							<li><solution>
								We need to figure out wheter
								<me>
									x_{1} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
									+ x_{2}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
									+ x_{3} \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
								</me>
								has a non-zero solution. We reuse our computation from <xref ref="soln-3-2-4a"/> for the case <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}</m>:
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\matr{ccc|c}
										{
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp a
										 \\
										 2 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp b
										 \\
										 2 \amp -1 \amp 1 \amp c
										 \\
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp d
										}
										\amp\overset{\text{row reduction}}{\longrightarrow}
										\matr{ccc|c}
										{
										 1 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp 0
										 \\
										 0 \amp -15 \amp 0 \amp 0
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0
										}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
									\amp\overset{2R_{2}+15R_{1}}{\longrightarrow}
										\matr{ccc|c}
										{
										 15 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
										 \\
										 0 \amp -15 \amp 0 \amp 0
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
										 \\
										 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0
										}.
									</mrow>
								</md>
									From this, we see that the only solution to the system of equations
									<me>
										x_{1} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
										+ x_{2}\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ -1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
										+ x_{3} \begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}
										=
										\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}
									</me>
									is <m>(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})=(0,0,0)</m>. Thus, the set <m>S</m> is linearly independent.
							</solution></li>
						</ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol>
							<li><answer>No, <m>S</m> does not span the set of all <m>2\times 2</m> matrices.
							</answer></li>
							<li><answer>
								Yes, the set <m>S</m> is linearly independent.
							</answer></li>
						</ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>
						<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.14) </p></aside>
							Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m> B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp k \end{bmatrix}</m>.  Is it possible to find <m>k</m> such that <m> AB = BA</m>? If so, what should <m> k </m> equal? 
						</statement>
						<hint>
							Compute both <m>AB</m> and <m>BA</m> and compare the answer.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							We compute
							<me>
								AB = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \amp 2+2k \\ 15 \amp 6+4k \end{bmatrix}
								\text{ and }
								BA = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \amp 10 \\ 3+3k \amp 6+4k \end{bmatrix}.
							</me>
							For these to be equal, we need them to be equal entrywise. The <m>(1,1)</m>- and the <m>(2,2)</m>-entry coincide for every choice of <m>k</m>, and for the other two entries we need
							<me> 2 + 2k = 10, \text{ i.e. } k = 4, \text{ and also }15 = 3+3k, \text{ i.e. } k= 4.</me>
						We see that <m>k=4</m> makes <m>AB=BA</m>.
						</solution>
						<answer>
							Yes, <m>k=4</m>.
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

						<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
							<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.15) </p></aside>
							Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m> B = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp k \end{bmatrix}</m>.  Is it possible to find <m>k</m> such that <m> AB = BA</m>? If so, what should <m> k </m> equal? 
						</statement>
						<hint>
							Compute both <m>AB</m> and <m>BA</m> and compare the answer.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							We compute
							<me>
								AB = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2+2k \\ 7 \amp 6+4k \end{bmatrix}
								\text{ and }
								BA = \begin{bmatrix} 7 \amp 10 \\ 1+3k \amp 6+4k \end{bmatrix}.
							</me>
							For these to be equal, we need them to be equal entrywise, but no matter what <m>k</m> we choose, the <m>(1,1)</m>-entries will never coincide (<m>3\neq 7</m>). Thus, the answer is no.
					</solution>
						<answer>
							No.
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
						<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.16) </p></aside>
						Let <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> be square matrices of the same size. 
						<ol>
							<li>
								If <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are symmetric, then so is <m> A - B </m>. 
							</li>						
							<li>
								If <m>A</m> is symmetric, then so is <m> kA </m> for any scalar <m> k </m>.
							</li>
						</ol>
					</statement>
					<hint>See <xref ref="hint-def-symmetric"/> for the defintion of symmetric.</hint>
					<!-- <hint>
						</hint> -->
						<solution>
							<ol>
							<li><solution>
								Let <m>A=[a_{ij}]</m> and <m>B=[b_{ij}]</m>, so that <m>A-B=[a_{ij}-b_{ij}]</m>. Since <m>A=A^T</m>, we have <m>a_{ij} = a_{ji}</m> for all choices of <m>i,j</m>, and similarly <m>b_{ij} = b_{ji}</m>. Thus,
								<md>
									<mrow>(A-B)^{T} \amp= [a_{ij}-b_{ij}]^{T} = [a_{ji}-b_{ji}] </mrow>
									<mrow>\amp= [a_{ij}-b_{ij}]  =  [a_{ij}]-[b_{ij}]  = A-B,</mrow>
								</md>
								so <m>A-B</m> is symmetric.
							</solution>
						</li>
							<li><solution>
								We need to show that <m>(kA)^{T} = k A</m> to conclude that <m>kA</m> is symmetric. Since equality of matrices is entrywise equality, we will consider their <m>(i,j)</m>-entries:
								<p>Let <m>A=[a_{ij}]</m>. By definition of scalar multiplication, <m>kA=[ka_{ij}]</m>. By definition of the transpose, the <m>(i,j)</m>-entry of <m>(kA)^{T}</m> is therefore <m>ka_{ji}</m> (where we swapped the roles of <m>i</m> and <m>j</m>).</p>
								<p>Since <m>A</m> is symmetric, we know that <m>a_{ij}=a_{ji}</m> for any choice of <m>i,j</m>, so in particular <m>ka_{ij}=ka_{ji}</m> also. This means that the <m>(i,j)</m>-entry of <m>kA</m> (namely <m>ka_{ij}</m>) coincides with the <m>(i,j)</m>-entry of <m>(kA)^{T}</m> (namely <m>ka_{ji}</m>), which shows that <m> k A = (kA)^{T} </m> since they are equal entrywise.</p>
							</solution>
							</li>
						</ol>
						</solution>
				</exercise></p>
						<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
						<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KK" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.29) </p></aside>
						A square matrix is called <em> skew-symmetric </em> if <m> A^T = -A </m>.  Show that the main diagonal of a skew-symmetric matrix consists of only zeros.
				</statement>
						<hint>
							If <m>A=[a_{ij}]</m>, then the main diagonal consists of every entry of the matrix which is of the form <m> a_{ii} </m>.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							Write <m>A=[a_{ij}]</m>. By assumption, 
							<me>
								[a_{ji}] = A^{T} = -A = [-a_{ij}],
							</me>
							so that <m>a_{ji}=-a_{ij} </m> for all choices of <m>i,j</m>. In particular, if <m>i=j</m>, then <m>a_{ii}=-a_{ii} </m>, so <m>a_{ii}=0</m>.
						</solution>
				</exercise> </p>

				<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>
						<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN" />, Chapter 2, Exercise 2.1.17) </p></aside>
						Show that <m> A + A^T </m> is symmetric for <em> any </em> square matrix <m> A </m>.
				</statement>
						<hint>
							See <xref ref="hint-def-symmetric"/> for the definition of symmetric.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							Recall first that <m>(A+B)^T = A^T + B^T</m> for any matrices <m>A, B</m> of the same size. Now, since <m>A</m> is square, <m>A</m> and <m>A^T</m> are of the same size, so we may use this fact for <m>B=A^T</m>:
							<md>
								<mrow> (A+A^T)^T \amp= A^T + (A^T)^T</mrow>
								<mrow> \amp = A^T + A,\qquad\text{ since } (A^T)^=A</mrow>
								<mrow> \amp = A + A^T,\qquad\text{ since addition is commutative.}</mrow>
							</md>
							This shows that <m>A+A^T</m> is its own transpose, i.e. symmetric.
						</solution>
						<!--<answer>
						</answer> -->

				</exercise> </p>
				</exercises>




		